# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: qemu-emulator
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:qemu-emulator/binary-translation] In computing, **binary translation** is a form of binary recompilation where sequences of instructions are translated from a source instruction set (ISA) to the target instruction set with respect to the operating system for which the binary was compiled.
[src:qemu-emulator/binary-translation] In some cases such as instruction set simulation, the target instruction set may be the same as the source instruction set, providing testing and debugging features such as instruction trace, conditional breakpoints and hot spot detection.
[src:qemu-emulator/binary-translation] The two main types are static and dynamic binary translation.
[src:qemu-emulator/binary-translation] Translation can be done in hardware (for example, by circuits in a CPU) or in software (e.g. run-time engines, static recompiler, emulators; all are typically slow).
[src:qemu-emulator/binary-translation] Binary translation is motivated by a lack of a binary for a target platform, the lack of source code to compile for the target platform, or otherwise difficulty in compiling the source for the target platform.
[src:qemu-emulator/binary-translation] Statically recompiled binaries run potentially faster than their respective emulated binaries, as the emulation overhead is removed.
[src:qemu-emulator/binary-translation] This is similar to the difference in performance between interpreted and compiled programs in general.
[src:qemu-emulator/binary-translation] A translator using static binary translation aims to convert all of the code of an executable file into code that runs on the target architecture and platform without having to run the code first, as is done in dynamic binary translation.
[src:qemu-emulator/binary-translation] This is very difficult to do correctly, since not all the code can be discovered by the translator.
[src:qemu-emulator/binary-translation] For example, some parts of the executable may be reachable only through indirect branches, whose value is known only at run-time.
[src:qemu-emulator/binary-translation] In experiments of PowerPC-to-x86 translations, some binaries even outperformed native versions, but on average they ran at two-thirds of native speed.
[src:qemu-emulator/binary-translation] In the 1960s Honeywell provided a program called the Liberator for their Honeywell 200 series of computers; it could translate programs for the IBM 1400 series of computers into programs for the Honeywell 200 series.
[src:qemu-emulator/binary-translation] In 1995 Norman Ramsey at Bell Communications Research and Mary F.
[src:qemu-emulator/binary-translation] Fernandez at Department of Computer Science, Princeton University developed *The New Jersey Machine-Code Toolkit* that had the basic tools for static assembly translation.
[src:qemu-emulator/binary-translation] Hutchinson at Nintendo developed a tool to generate "C" code from Game Boy binary that could then be compiled for a new platform and linked against a hardware library for use in airline entertainment systems.
[src:qemu-emulator/binary-translation] In 2014, an ARM architecture version of the 1998 video game *StarCraft* was generated by static recompilation and additional reverse engineering of the original x86 version.
[src:qemu-emulator/binary-translation] The Pandora handheld community was capable of developing the required tools on their own and achieving such translations successfully several times.
[src:qemu-emulator/binary-translation] Another example is the NES-to-x86 statically recompiled version of the videogame *Super Mario Bros.* which was generated under usage of LLVM in 2013.
[src:qemu-emulator/binary-translation] For instance, a successful x86-to-x64 static recompilation was generated for the procedural terrain generator of the video game *Cube World* in 2014.
[src:qemu-emulator/binary-translation] Dynamic binary translation (DBT) looks at a short sequence of code—typically on the order of a single basic block—then translates it and caches the resulting sequence.
[src:qemu-emulator/binary-translation] Code is only translated as it is discovered and when possible, and branch instructions are made to point to already translated and saved code (memoization).
[src:qemu-emulator/binary-translation] Dynamic binary translation differs from simple emulation (eliminating the emulator's main read-decode-execute loop—a major performance bottleneck), paying for this by large overhead during translation time.
[src:qemu-emulator/binary-translation] This overhead is hopefully amortized as translated code sequences are executed multiple times.
[src:qemu-emulator/binary-translation] More advanced dynamic translators employ dynamic recompilation where the translated code is instrumented to find out what portions are executed a large number of times, and these portions are optimized aggressively.
[src:qemu-emulator/binary-translation] This technique is reminiscent of a JIT compiler, and in fact such compilers (e.g.
[src:qemu-emulator/binary-translation] Sun's HotSpot technology) can be viewed as dynamic translators from a virtual instruction set (the bytecode) to a real one.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] In computing, an **emulator** is hardware or software that enables one computer system (called the *host*) to behave like another computer system (called the *guest*).
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] An emulator typically enables the host system to run software or use peripheral devices designed for the guest system.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] Emulation refers to the ability of a computer program in an electronic device to emulate (or imitate) another program or device.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] Many printers, for example, are designed to emulate HP LaserJet printers because a significant amount of software is written specifically for HP models.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] If a non-HP printer emulates an HP printer, any software designed for an actual HP printer will also function on the non-HP device, producing equivalent print results.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] A hardware emulator is an emulator which takes the form of a hardware device.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] Examples include the DOS-compatible card installed in some 1990s-era Macintosh computers, such as the Centris 610 or Performa 630, that allowed them to run personal computer (PC) software programs and field-programmable gate array-based hardware emulators.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] The Church–Turing thesis implies that theoretically, any operating environment can be emulated within any other environment, assuming memory limitations are ignored.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] However, in practice, it can be quite difficult, particularly when the exact behavior of the system to be emulated is not documented and has to be deduced through reverse engineering.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] It also says nothing about timing constraints; if the emulator does not perform as quickly as it did using the original hardware, the software inside the emulation may run much more slowly (possibly triggering timer interrupts that alter behavior).
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] Most emulators just emulate a hardware architecture—if operating system firmware or software is required for the desired software, it must be provided as well (and may itself be emulated).
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] Both the OS and the software will then be interpreted by the emulator, rather than being run by native hardware.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] While emulation could, if taken to the extreme, go down to the atomic level, basing its output on a simulation of the actual circuitry from a virtual power source, this would be a highly unusual solution.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] Emulators typically stop at a simulation of the documented hardware specifications and digital logic.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] Sufficient emulation of some hardware platforms requires extreme accuracy, down to the level of individual clock cycles, undocumented features, unpredictable analog elements, and implementation bugs.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] This is particularly the case with classic home computers such as the Commodore 64, whose software often depends on highly sophisticated low-level programming tricks invented by game programmers and the "demoscene".
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] In contrast, some other platforms have had very little use of direct hardware addressing, such as an emulator for the PlayStation 4.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] In these cases, a simple compatibility layer may suffice.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] This translates system calls for the foreign system into system calls for the host system e.g., the Linux compatibility layer used on *BSD to run closed source Linux native software on FreeBSD and NetBSD.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] Developers of software for embedded systems or video game consoles often design their software on especially accurate emulators called simulators before trying it on the real hardware.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] This is so that software can be produced and tested before the final hardware exists in large quantities, so that it can be tested without taking the time to copy the program to be debugged at a low level and without introducing the side effects of a debugger.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] In many cases, the simulator is actually produced by the company providing the hardware, which theoretically increases its accuracy.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] Math co-processor emulators allow programs compiled with math instructions to run on machines that do not have the co-processor installed, but the extra work done by the CPU may slow the system down.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] If a math coprocessor is not installed or present on the CPU, when the CPU executes any co-processor instruction it will make a determined interrupt (coprocessor not available), calling the math emulator routines.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] When the instruction is successfully emulated, the program continues executing.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] Logic simulation is the use of a computer program to simulate the operation of a digital circuit such as a processor.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] This is done after a digital circuit has been designed in logic equations, but before the circuit is fabricated in hardware.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] Functional simulation is the use of a computer program to simulate the execution of a second computer program written in symbolic assembly language or compiler language, rather than in binary machine code.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] By using a functional simulator, programmers can execute and trace selected sections of source code to search for programming errors (bugs), without generating binary code.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] This is distinct from simulating execution of binary code, which is software emulation.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] The first functional simulator was written by Autonetics about 1960 for testing assembly language programs for later execution in military computer D-17B.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] This made it possible for flight programs to be written, executed, and tested before D-17B computer hardware had been built.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] Autonetics also programmed a functional simulator for testing flight programs for later execution in the military computer D-37C.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] Video game console emulators are programs that allow a personal computer or video game console to emulate another video game console.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] They are most often used to play older 1980s to 2000s-era video games on modern personal computers and more contemporary video game consoles.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] They are also used to translate games into other languages, to modify existing games, and in the development process of "home brew" DIY demos and in the creation of new games for older systems.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] The Internet has helped in the spread of console emulators, as most - if not all - would be unavailable for sale in retail outlets.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] Examples of console emulators that have been released in the last few decades are: RPCS3, Dolphin, Cemu, PCSX2, PPSSPP, ZSNES, Citra, ePSXe, Project64, Visual Boy Advance, Nestopia, and Yuzu.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] Due to their popularity, emulators have been impersonated by malware.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] Most of these emulators are for video game consoles like the Xbox 360, Xbox One, Nintendo 3DS, etc.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] Generally such emulators make currently impossible claims such as being able to run Xbox One and Xbox 360 games in a single program.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] As computers and global computer networks continued to advance and emulator developers grew more skilled in their work, the length of time between the commercial release of a console and its successful emulation began to shrink.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] Fifth generation consoles such as Nintendo 64, PlayStation and sixth generation handhelds, such as the Game Boy Advance, saw significant progress toward emulation during their production.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] This led to an effort by console manufacturers to stop unofficial emulation, but consistent failures such as *Sega v.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] 1992), *Sony Computer Entertainment, Inc. v.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] Connectix Corporation* 203 F.3d 596 (2000), and *Sony Computer Entertainment America v.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] According to all legal precedents, emulation is legal within the United States.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] However, unauthorized distribution of copyrighted code remains illegal, according to both country-specific copyright and international copyright law under the Berne Convention.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] Under United States law, obtaining a dumped copy of the original machine's BIOS is legal under the ruling *Lewis Galoob Toys, Inc. v.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] 1992) as fair use as long as the user obtained a legally purchased copy of the machine.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] To mitigate this however, several emulators for platforms such as Game Boy Advance are capable of running without a BIOS file, using high-level emulation to simulate BIOS subroutines at a slight cost in emulation accuracy.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] Terminal emulators are software programs that provide modern computers and devices interactive access to applications running on mainframe computer operating systems or other host systems such as HP-UX or OpenVMS.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] Terminals such as the IBM 3270 or VT100 and many others are no longer produced as physical devices.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] Instead, software running on modern operating systems simulates a "dumb" terminal and is able to render the graphical and text elements of the host application, send keystrokes and process commands using the appropriate terminal protocol.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] Some terminal emulation applications include Attachmate Reflection, IBM Personal Communications, and Micro Focus Rumba.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] Typically, an emulator is divided into modules that correspond roughly to the emulated computer's subsystems.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] Buses are often not emulated, either for reasons of performance or simplicity, and virtual peripherals communicate directly with the CPU or the memory subsystem.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] It is possible for the memory subsystem emulation to be reduced to simply an array of elements each sized like an emulated word; however, this model fails very quickly as soon as any location in the computer's logical memory does not match physical memory.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] This clearly is the case whenever the emulated hardware allows for advanced memory management (in which case, the MMU logic can be embedded in the memory emulator, made a module of its own, or sometimes integrated into the CPU simulator).
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] Features such as bank switching or segmentation may also complicate memory emulation.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] As a result, most emulators implement at least two procedures for writing to and reading from logical memory, and it is these procedures' duty to map every access to the correct location of the correct object.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] The CPU simulator is often the most complicated part of an emulator.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] Many emulators are written using "pre-packaged" CPU simulators, in order to concentrate on good and efficient emulation of a specific machine.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] This is made possible by assigning a variable to each register and flag of the simulated CPU.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] The logic of the simulated CPU can then more or less be directly translated into software algorithms, creating a software re-implementation that basically mirrors the original hardware implementation.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] The following example illustrates how CPU simulation can be accomplished by an interpreter.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] In this case, interrupts are checked-for before every instruction executed, though this behavior is rare in real emulators for performance reasons (it is generally faster to use a subroutine to do the work of an interrupt).
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] Interpreters are very popular as computer simulators, as they are much simpler to implement than more time-efficient alternative solutions, and their speed is more than adequate for emulating computers of more than roughly a decade ago on modern machines.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] However, the speed penalty inherent in interpretation can be a problem when emulating computers whose processor speed is on the same order of magnitude as the host machine.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] Until not many years ago, emulation in such situations was considered completely impractical by many.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] What allowed breaking through this restriction were the advances in dynamic recompilation techniques.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] The translated code is kept in a *code cache*, and the original code is not lost or affected; this way, even data segments can be (meaninglessly) translated by the recompiler, resulting in no more than a waste of translation time.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] Speed may not be desirable as some older games were not designed with the speed of faster computers in mind.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] A game designed for a 30 MHz PC with a level timer of 300 game seconds might only give the player 30 seconds on a 300 MHz PC.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] Other programs, such as some DOS programs, may not even run on faster computers.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] Most emulators do not, as mentioned earlier, emulate the main system bus; each I/O device is thus often treated as a special case, and no consistent interface for virtual peripherals is provided.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] A unified I/O API may not necessarily mirror the structure of the real hardware bus: bus design is limited by several electric constraints and a need for hardware concurrency management that can mostly be ignored in a software implementation.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] Emulation is one strategy in pursuit of digital preservation and combating obsolescence.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] Emulation focuses on recreating an original computer environment, which can be time-consuming and difficult to achieve, but valuable because of its ability to maintain a closer connection to the authenticity of the digital object, operating system, or even gaming platform.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] Emulation addresses the original hardware and software environment of the digital object, and recreates it on a current machine.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] The emulator allows the user to have access to any kind of application or operating system on a current platform, while the software runs as it did in its original environment.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] He further states that this should not only apply to out of date systems, but also be upwardly mobile to future unknown systems.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] Because of its primary use of digital formats, new media art relies heavily on emulation as a preservation strategy.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] Artists such as Cory Arcangel specialize in resurrecting obsolete technologies in their artwork and recognize the importance of a decentralized and deinstitutionalized process for the preservation of digital culture.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] In many cases, the goal of emulation in new media art is to preserve a digital medium so that it can be saved indefinitely and reproduced without error, so that there is no reliance on hardware that ages and becomes obsolete.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] The paradox is that the emulation and the emulator have to be made to work on future computers.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] Emulation techniques are commonly used during the design and development of new systems.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] It eases the development process by providing the ability to detect, recreate and repair flaws in the design even before the system is actually built.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] It is particularly useful in the design of multi-core systems, where concurrency errors can be very difficult to detect and correct without the controlled environment provided by virtual hardware.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] This also allows the software development to take place before the hardware is ready, thus helping to validate design decisions and give a little more control.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] The word "emulator" was coined in 1963 at IBM during development of the NPL (IBM System/360) product line, using a "new combination of software, microcode, and hardware".
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] They discovered that simulation using additional instructions implemented in microcode and hardware, instead of software simulation using only standard instructions, to execute programs written for earlier IBM computers dramatically increased simulation speed.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] Earlier, IBM provided simulators for, e.g., the 650 on the 705.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] In addition to simulators, IBM had compatibility features on the 709 and 7090, for which it provided the IBM 709 computer with a program to run legacy programs written for the IBM 704 on the 709 and later on the IBM 7090.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] This program used the instructions added by the compatibility feature to trap instructions requiring special handling; all other 704 instructions ran the same on a 7090.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] The compatibility feature on the 1410 only required setting a console toggle switch, not a support program.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] In 1963, when microcode was first used to speed up this simulation process, IBM engineers coined the term "emulator" to describe the concept.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] In the 2000s, it has become common to use the word "emulate" in the context of software.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] However, before 1980, "emulation" referred only to emulation with a hardware or microcode assist, while "simulation" referred to pure software emulation.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] For example, a computer specially built for running programs designed for another architecture is an emulator.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] In contrast, a simulator could be a program which runs on a PC, so that old Atari games can be simulated on it.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] Purists continue to insist on this distinction, but currently the term "emulation" often means the complete imitation of a machine executing binary code while "simulation" often refers to computer simulation, where a computer program is used to simulate an abstract model.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] Computer simulation is used in virtually every scientific and engineering domain and Computer Science is no exception, with several projects simulating abstract models of computer systems, such as network simulation, which both practically and semantically differs from network emulation.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] Hardware virtualization is the virtualization of computers as complete hardware platforms, certain logical abstractions of their components, or only the functionality required to run various operating systems.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] Virtualization hides the physical characteristics of a computing platform from the users, presenting instead an abstract computing platform.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] At its origins, the software that controlled virtualization was called a "control program", but the terms "hypervisor" or "virtual machine monitor" became preferred over time.
[src:qemu-emulator/emulator] Each hypervisor can manage or run multiple virtual machines.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] The **Quick Emulator** (**QEMU**) is a free and open-source machine emulator and virtualizer.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] As a Virtual Machine Monitor (VMM) it supports a number of hypervisors, including the Linux-based Kernel-based Virtual Machine (KVM), Xen, MacOS's HVF, Windows' Hyper-V and a number of others.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] It is also capable of emulating a number of instruction set architectures on any supported host through its JIT binary translator known as the Tiny Code Generator (TCG).
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] This allows it to emulate full systems or run individual programs compiled for one processor architecture on any other.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] QEMU supports the emulation of x86, ARM, PowerPC, RISC-V, and many others.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] QEMU is free software originally developed by Fabrice Bellard; the first preview release was in 2003.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] Different components of QEMU are licensed under the GNU General Public License (GPL), BSD license, GNU Lesser General Public License (LGPL), or other GPL-compatible licenses.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] QEMU supports the emulation of various architectures, including x86, MIPS64 (up to Release 6), SPARC (sun4m and sun4u), ARM (Integrator/CP and Versatile/PB), SuperH, PowerPC (PReP and Power Macintosh), ETRAX CRIS, MicroBlaze, and RISC-V.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] It supports saving the virtual machine state while all programs are running.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] Guest operating systems do not need patching to run inside QEMU.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] The virtual machine can interface with many types of physical host hardware, including the user's hard disks, CD-ROM drives, network cards, audio interfaces, and USB devices.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] USB devices can be emulated entirely, or the host's USB devices can be used, although this requires administrator privileges and does not work with some devices.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] Virtual disk images can be stored in QCOW format, which can significantly reduce image size.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] QCOW images only occupy the actual used disk space, not the full configured capacity.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] This means a configured 120 GB disk may only occupy a few hundred megabytes on the host, as QCOW does not store unused disk space in the image file.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] The QCOW2 format also allows the creation of overlay images, which are files that store only the changes made from an original (unmodified) base image file.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] This enables the emulated disk's contents to be reverted to an earlier state.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] For instance, a base image could contain a fresh installation of a known working operating system, and overlay images can be used to record changes.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] Should the guest system become unusable (through virus attack, accidental system destruction, etc.), the user can delete the overlay and use an earlier emulated disk image.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] QEMU can emulate network cards (of different models) that share the host system's connectivity by translating network addresses, effectively allowing the guest to use the same network as the host.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] The virtual network cards can also connect to network cards of other instances of QEMU or to local TAP interfaces.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] Network connectivity can also be achieved by bridging a TUN/TAP interface used by QEMU with a non-virtual Ethernet interface on the host OS using the host OS's bridging features.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] QEMU integrates several services to allow the host and guest systems to communicate for example: an integrated SMB server and network-port redirection (to allow incoming connections to the virtual machine).
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] It can also boot Linux kernels without a bootloader.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] QEMU does not depend on the presence of graphical output methods on the host system.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] Instead, it provides access to the guest OS screen via an integrated VNC server.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] It can also use an emulated serial line without any screen, with applicable operating systems.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] Simulating multiple CPUs running SMP is possible.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] QEMU does not require administrative rights to run unless additional kernel modules are used to improve speed (like KQEMU) or certain modes of its network connectivity model are utilized.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] Since QEMU Version 0.10.0 the Tiny Code Generator (TCG) replaced the previous *DynGen* system, which relied on GCC 3.x to work.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] As QEMU runs basic blocks of target code are translated into an machine-independent intermediate representation known as *TCG ops*.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] The operations then go through a simple optimization passes before being passed to the backend which will emit target code for the host's architecture.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] TCG requires dedicated code written to support every architecture it runs on, so that the JIT knows what to translate the *TCG ops* to.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] If no dedicated JIT code is available for the architecture, TCG falls back to a slow interpreter mode called TCG Interpreter (TCI).
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] KQEMU was a Linux kernel module, also written by Fabrice Bellard, which notably sped up emulation of x86 or x86-64 guests on platforms with the same CPU architecture.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] This worked by running user mode code (and optionally some kernel code) directly on the host computer's CPU, and by using processor and peripheral emulation only for kernel-mode and real-mode code.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] KQEMU could execute code from many guest operating systems even if the host CPU did not support hardware-assisted virtualization.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] KQEMU was initially a closed-source product available free of charge but starting from version 1.3.0pre10 (February 2007), it was relicensed under the GNU General Public License.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] QEMU versions starting with 0.12.0 (as of August 2009) support large memory which makes them incompatible with KQEMU.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] Newer releases of QEMU have completely removed support for KQEMU.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] QVM86 was a GNU GPLv2 licensed drop-in replacement for the then closed-source KQEMU.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] The developers of QVM86 ceased development in January 2007.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] Kernel-based Virtual Machine (*KVM*) has mostly taken over as the Linux-based hardware-assisted virtualization solution for use with QEMU following the lack of support for KQEMU and QVM86.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] QEMU can also use KVM on other architectures like ARM and MIPS.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] Intel's Hardware Accelerated Execution Manager (*HAXM*) is an open-source alternative to KVM for x86-based hardware-assisted virtualization on NetBSD, Linux, Windows and macOS using Intel VT.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] As of 2013 Intel mostly solicits its use with QEMU for Android development.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] Starting with version 2.9.0, the official QEMU includes support for HAXM, under the name *Hax*.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] QEMU supports a number of disk image formats.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] QEMU can also directly access host devices and partitions which allows it to work with other storage technologies like iSCSI, LVM, LUKS, NBD, NVMe and ZFS.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] It can also support exporting a file-system into a Virtual VFAT device.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] The **QEMU Object Model** (QOM) provides a framework for registering types that users can make and instantiating objects from those types.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] Virtualization solutions that use QEMU can execute multiple virtual CPUs in parallel.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] For user-mode emulation, QEMU maps emulated threads to host threads.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] QEMU can run a host thread for each emulated virtual CPU (vCPU) for full system emulation.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] This depends on the guest being updated to support parallel system emulation, currently ARM, Alpha, HP-PA, PowerPC, RISC-V, s390x, x86, and Xtensa.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] Otherwise, a single thread is used to emulate all virtual CPUs (vCPUs), which executes each vCPU in a round-robin manner.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] VirtualBox, first released in January 2007, used some of QEMU's virtual hardware devices, and had a built-in dynamic re-compiler based on QEMU.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] As with KQEMU, VirtualBox runs nearly all guest code natively on the host via the VMM (Virtual Machine Manager) and uses the re-compiler only as a fallback mechanism – for example, when guest code executes in real mode.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] In addition, VirtualBox did a lot of code analysis and patching using a built-in disassembler to minimize recompilation.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] VirtualBox is free and open-source (available under GPL), except for certain features.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] Xen, a virtual machine monitor, can run in HVM (hardware virtual machine) mode, using Intel VT-x or AMD-V hardware x86 virtualization extensions and ARM Cortex-A7 and Cortex-A15 virtualization extensions.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] This means that instead of para-virtualized devices, a real set of virtual hardware is exposed to the DomU, enabling it to use real device drivers.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] QEMU includes several components: CPU emulators, emulated devices, generic devices, machine descriptions, user interface, and a debugger.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] The emulated devices and generic devices in QEMU make up its device models for I/O virtualization.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] They comprise a PIIX3 IDE (with some rudimentary PIIX4 capabilities), Cirrus Logic or plain VGA emulated video, RTL8139 or E1000 network emulation, and ACPI support.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] Xen-HVM utilizes device emulation based on the QEMU project to deliver I/O virtualization to virtual machines (VMs).
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] Hardware is emulated through a QEMU "device model" daemon running as a backend in Dom0.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] Unlike other QEMU modes, such as dynamic translation or KVM, the hypervisor fully manages virtual CPUs, pausing them as necessary while QEMU handles memory-mapped I/O emulation.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] KVM (Kernel-based Virtual Machine) is a FreeBSD and Linux kernel module that allows a user space program access to the hardware virtualization features of various processors, with which QEMU can offer virtualization for x86, PowerPC, and S/390 guests.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] When the target architecture is the same as the host architecture, QEMU can make use of KVM particular features, such as acceleration.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] In early 2005, Win4Lin introduced Win4Lin Pro Desktop, based on a 'tuned' version of QEMU and KQEMU and it hosts NT-versions of Windows.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] In June 2006, Win4Lin released Win4Lin Virtual Desktop Server based on the same code base.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] Win4Lin Virtual Desktop Server serves Microsoft Windows sessions to thin clients from a Linux server.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] In September 2006, Win4Lin announced a change of the company name to Virtual Bridges with the release of Win4BSD Pro Desktop, a port of the product to FreeBSD and PC-BSD.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] Solaris support followed in May 2007 with the release of Win4Solaris Pro Desktop and Win4Solaris Virtual Desktop Server.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] SerialICE is a QEMU-based firmware debugging tool running system firmware inside of QEMU while accessing real hardware through a serial connection to a host system.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] This can be used as a cheap replacement for hardware in-circuit emulators (ICE).
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] WinUAE introduced support for the CyberStorm PPC and Blizzard 603e boards using the QEMU PPC core in version 3.0.0.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] Unicorn is a CPU emulation framework based on QEMU's "TCG" CPU emulator.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] Unlike QEMU, Unicorn focuses on the CPU *only*: no emulation of any peripherals is provided and raw binary code (outside of the context of an executable file or a system image) can be run directly.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] Unicorn is thread-safe and has multiple bindings and instrumentation interfaces.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] Limbo is an x86 and ARM64 QEMU-based virtual machine for Android.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] It is one of the few pieces of virtual machine software available for Android capable of emulating Microsoft Windows, although it was designed to emulate Linux and DOS.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] Unlike other QEMU-based emulators, it does not require users to type commands to use, instead having a user interface to set the virtual machine's settings.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] It is more popular in developing countries in Asia such as India, Malaysia, and Thailand on YouTube due to the high usage of the Android Operating System.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] Limbo was removed from the Google Play Store for unknown reasons between February 2019 and December 2020, though it can still be installed off the developer's website with an APK (Android Package) installation.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] Limbo tends to have issues regarding its audio quality and playback.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] No fixes have been found for these problems as of 2024.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] Overall, Limbo is less well-known than other virtual machine software, which leads to less available information regarding its troubleshooting.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] It is required to install an application known as "Hacker's Keyboard" to use many keyboard functions that a basic Android keyboard cannot do in Limbo x86, such as the Ctrl, Alt, Del, and function keys.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] It is recommended to install Hacker's Keyboard with an APK file, as the Google Play version says it doesn't work with newer versions of Android.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] QEMU can emulate the i386 and x86_64 architectures.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] The BIOS implementation used by QEMU starting from version 0.12 is SeaBIOS.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] The VGA BIOS implementation of SeaBIOS is also used starting from version 2.0.0.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] On the PREP target, *Open Hack'Ware*, an Open-Firmware-compatible BIOS, is used.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] On the sPAPR target, another Open-Firmware-compatible BIOS is used, called SLOF.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] QEMU emulates the ARMv7 instruction set (and down to ARMv5TEJ) with NEON extension.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] It emulates full systems like Integrator/CP board, Versatile baseboard, RealView Emulation baseboard, XScale-based PDAs, Palm Tungsten|E PDA, Nokia N800 and Nokia N810 Internet tablets, etc.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] QEMU also powers the Android emulator which is part of the Android SDK (most current Android implementations are ARM-based).
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] Starting from version 2.0.0 of their Bada SDK, Samsung has chosen QEMU to help development on emulated 'Wave' devices.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] In 1.5.0 and 1.6.0, Samsung Exynos 4210 (dual-core Cortex-A9) and Versatile Express ARM Cortex-A9 ARM Cortex-A15 are emulated.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] In 1.6.0, the 32-bit instructions of the ARMv8 (AArch64) architecture are emulated, but 64-bit instructions are unsupported.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] QEMU can emulate 64-bit "A-profile" CPUs that commonly run Linux such as the ARM Cortex-A53, ARM Cortex-A57 and the ARM Cortex-A72.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] This allows it to emulate the Raspberry Pi 3 and 4.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] QEMU has support for both 32- and 64-bit SPARC architectures.
[src:qemu-emulator/qemu] When the firmware in the JavaStation (sun4m Architecture) was updated to version 0.8.1, Proll—a PROM replacement—was replaced with OpenBIOS in version 0.8.2.
